‘How does the pattern of disturbance accumulate over time?’

Maximilian H.K. Hesselbarth

16 April, 2020

Introduction

Please be aware and acknowledge that the data was published in: Klaas, B.A., Moloney, K.A., Danielson, B.J., 2000. The tempo and mode of gopher mound production in a tallgrass prairie remnant. Ecography 23, 246–256.

For all further use of the data, a permission of the author must be obtained. We also ask you to not redistribute the data without asking for permission. For further questions about the data, please contact kmoloney@iastate.edu!

Set-up

First, we load the spatstat library for spatial point pattern analysis (Baddeley and Turner, 2005). Also, we import the tidyverse library, a collection of R packages designed for data science (Wickham, 2017). To reproduce the analysis we also need to load the raster (Hijmans, 2019) package and for an easy layout of result plots, the patchwork (Pedersen, 2019) package.

# load packages
library(spatstat)
library(tidyverse)
library(raster)
library(patchwork)

If you don’t have the packages installed yet, run the following code in order to install them.

# install packages if not installed yed
install.packages(c("spatstat", "tidyverse", "raster", "patchwork"))

Throughout this tutorial, I’m going to use the pipe-operator %>%. This allows to redirect (or pipe) the result of a function call directly into the next function. The big advantage of this is that subsequent functions must not be nested and code is much easier to read.

# create 100 random numbers
x <- runif(n = 100)

# calculate the mean of the quantiles
mean(quantile(x))
## [1] 0.5082658

# same, but much easier to read
x %>%  
  quantile() %>% 
  mean()
## [1] 0.5082658

Import the data

We use the readr (Wickham et al., 2018) package to import the data because it will automatically be imported as a tibble (Müller and Wickham, 2019; an advanced data.frame). For more information see ?tibble. But, of course you can use any way of importing the data you prefer. The deliminator of the data is a comma. The data is seperated into two files for the years 1994 and 1995.

The data includes a coloumn with the date of sampling as well as a coloumn which identifies the type of the point (“Elevation”, “New”, “Old”, “Stake”, “Trap”) We transform the date coloumn as.Date and order the data by Type and Date in the same pipe.

data_94 <- readr::read_delim("Data/Mounds_94.csv", 
                             delim  = ",", col_names = TRUE) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(Date = as.Date(Date, format = "%m/%d/%y")) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(Type, Date)

data_95 <- readr::read_delim("Data/Mounds_95.csv", 
                             delim  = ",", col_names = TRUE) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(Date = as.Date(Date, format = "%m/%d/%y")) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(Type, Date)

To check the different types of points, we can use the table() function. Because we are only interested in the new mounds, we filter the data accordingly and save the result as a subset of the data.

# check different data types
table(data_94$Type, useNA = "ifany")
##

# filter new mounds
mounds_new_94 <- dplyr::filter(data_94, Type == "New")
mounds_new_95 <- dplyr::filter(data_95, Type == "New")

Firstly, we simply visualize the two point patterns of the north grid in 1994 and 1995. For this, we use the ggplot2 (Wickham, 2016) package. But again, you can also use base plot to plot the coordinates if you prefer. To also plot the study plot (or observation window), we create a tibble with the coordinates of the corner points in counter-clockwise order

# coordinates of study plot
study_plot <- tibble::tibble(x = c(0, 80, 80, 0), y = c(0, 0, 80, 80))

Next, we can build both plots and combine them into on plot using patchwork.

# create plot 1994
mounds_new_94_gg <- ggplot(data = mounds_new_94) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = X, y = Y)) + 
  geom_polygon(data = study_plot, aes(x = x, y = y), size = 1,
               fill = NA, col = "black") +
  coord_equal() + 
  labs(x = "", y = "", title = "N Grid 1994") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey"), 
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(colour = "grey"))

Intensity over time

Next, we can calculate the intensity over time. For this, we firstly convert to the tibble to a ppp-object (point pattern in 2-D plane) of the spatstat package. To specify the study plot (called “observation window” in spatstat), we can use the previously created tibble with the corner coordinates

# create owin object for study plot
study_plot <- spatstat::owin(poly = study_plot)

# create ppp new mounds
mounds_new_94_ppp <- spatstat::ppp(x = mounds_new_94$X, y = mounds_new_94$Y, 
                                   window = study_plot)
## Warning: 1 point was rejected as lying outside the specified window

mounds_new_95_ppp <- spatstat::ppp(x = mounds_new_95$X, y = mounds_new_95$Y, 
                                   window = study_plot)
## Warning: 3 points were rejected as lying outside the specified window

A few points are located slightly outside the defined study plot (probably due to some minor inaccurcies during the sampling). spatstat automatically rejects these points and we need to remove those points when we want to add the date as marks to the point pattern (additional characteristics of the points). For this, the inside.owin() function can be used.

# add marks to points but subsetting points outside study plot
spatstat::marks(mounds_new_94_ppp) <- mounds_new_94$Date[spatstat::inside.owin(x = mounds_new_94$X, 
                                                                               y = mounds_new_94$Y, 
                                                                               w = study_plot)]

spatstat::marks(mounds_new_95_ppp) <- mounds_new_95$Date[spatstat::inside.owin(x = mounds_new_95$X, 
                                                                               y = mounds_new_95$Y, 
                                                                               w = study_plot)]

As a last step, we superimpose the point pattern of 1994 and 1995 to have one final point pattern.

mounds_new_94_95_ppp <- spatstat::superimpose(mounds_new_94_ppp, mounds_new_95_ppp)

Now, we can use the moving window approach to calculate the intensity/rate per area and time. Therefore, we create a raster grid to later store the rate of production.

grid_plot <- matrix(data = 0, nrow = 80, ncol = 80) %>% 
  raster::raster(xmn = 0, xmx = 80, 
                 ymn = 0, ymx = 80, 
                 crs = NA)

To acutally count the number of mounds within each grid cell, we convert this raster to a tibble again to loop through all rows and by that through each raster cell. Within the loop, we create a small owin object with the size of 20 \(m^{2}\) using the cell centre as the centre of the owin. We then count the number of mounds within the window using inside.owin() and divide the count by the amount of time and the area.

# convert to dataframe
grid_plot_df <- raster::as.data.frame(grid_plot, xy = TRUE) %>% 
  tibble::as.tibble()
## Warning: `as.tibble()` is deprecated as of tibble 2.0.0.
## Please use `as_tibble()` instead.
## The signature and semantics have changed, see `?as_tibble`.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.

# init vector to store results
production_rate <- vector(mode = "numeric", length = nrow(grid_plot_df))

# count mounds in 20qm area
for (i in 1:nrow(grid_plot_df)) {
  
  # create owin with 20qm around cell center
  owin_temp <-  spatstat::owin(xrange = c(grid_plot_df[[i, 1]] - sqrt(5), 
                                          grid_plot_df[[i, 1]] + sqrt(5)), 
                               yrange = c(grid_plot_df[[i, 2]] - sqrt(5), 
                                          grid_plot_df[[i, 2]] + sqrt(5))) 
  
  # T/F for points inside
  points_inside_temp <- spatstat::inside.owin(x = mounds_new_94_95_ppp$x, 
                                              y = mounds_new_94_95_ppp$y, 
                                              w = owin_temp)
  
  # count number of trues divided by sample area and time
  production_rate[i] <- sum(points_inside_temp) / 20 / 2
}

Lastly, we can add the calculated production rate to the raster and/or the tibble and plot the result using either ggplot2 or the raster plotting function

# add value to df
grid_plot_df$layer <- production_rate

# add value to raster
raster::values(grid_plot) <- production_rate

# plot result
ggplot(data = grid_plot_df) + 
  geom_raster(aes(x = x, y = y, fill = layer)) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "C", 
                       name = expression(paste("Mounds ", m^{-2}, yr^{-1}))) + 
  coord_equal() + 
  labs(x = "", y = "", title = "N Grid 1994 - 1995") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey"), 
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(colour = "grey"))

Pooled L-function

To analyse the L-function for the pooled data set (both years combined), we firstly clip the study plot by removing the area that was flooded. Because we don’t know the exact locations of this area, we have to estimated it by try-and-error.

# new observation window w/o area with no mounds
study_plot_clipped <- tibble::tibble(x = c(0, 78, 76, 57, 34, 10, 0),
                                     y = c(0, 0 , 17, 67, 77, 80, 80))

# replace window
mounds_new_94_95_ppp$window <-  spatstat::owin(poly = study_plot_clipped)

In the original publication, the center L-function was used. However, in spatstat only the “normal” L-function is available. Thus, we need to center it ourselves. The eval.fv() functions allows to evaluate any expression involving the result of a summary function in spatstat (fv object). Alternativly, you could also use the center_l_function() function from the onpoint (Hesselbarth, 2019)

l_center <- function(x, ...) {

  # calculate L function
  x <- spatstat::Lest(x, ...)

  # get r value
  r <- x$r

  # center L-function by r value
  l_centered <- spatstat::eval.fv(x - r)

  return(l_centered)
}

To calculate the 5th highest and lowest values of the null model data and the observed function value, we use the envelope() function. If we do not specify a specifc null model, complete spatial randomness (CSR) is simulated automatically.

# calculate CSR envelopes
envelopes_l_fun <- spatstat::envelope(Y = mounds_new_94_95_ppp, 
                                      fun = l_center, 
                                      funargs = list(r = seq(from  = 0, to = 35, length.out = 525), 
                                                     correction = "Ripley"), 
                                      nsim = 199, nrank = 5,
                                      verbose = FALSE)

# plot results
plot(envelopes_l_fun, xlim = c(0, 35), ylim = c(-3, 7), main = "")
